<Section id="motivation" number="1" title="Motivation">
  <p>
    Pedestrian crowds under evacuation behave more like a coupled
    physical–psychological system than like a fluid through an orifice.
    Building codes and most agent-based models implicitly assume the
    latter, sizing exits to occupancy as if throughput were a function of
    geometry alone. The faster-is-slower (FIS) effect, first quantified
    by Helbing, Farkas and Vicsek (2000) [1], already shows the gap.
    Raising every agent's desired walking speed lowers the throughput of
    a narrow exit, because lateral contact forces lock pedestrians into
    self-supporting arches at the bottleneck. FIS is a property of the
    geometry and the contact physics alone. But it points at something
    larger: the desired speed is not a control parameter so much as an
    output of the agent's emotional state, and that state is contagious.
  </p>

  <p>
    The mechanism is well documented. In a crowd under threat, a single
    panicked individual visibly accelerates. Neighbours read the motion
    as a signal that the situation has changed, raise their own urgency,
    and pass the signal on. Within seconds, what began as one
    perturbation has crossed the room. The Social Force Model
    (Helbing and Molnár, 1995) [2] treats only the physical layer of
    this process: positions, velocities, social repulsion, contact
    friction. It is silent on the spread of the stress that drives
    desired speed in the first place. Bellomo and collaborators (2016)
    [7] identified this as the central modelling gap and proposed
    treating stress as a per-agent internal state that evolves under
    social interaction.
  </p>

  <p>
    The present work follows that suggestion. We assign every agent a
    stress level <Math tex={String.raw`\beta_i(t) \in [0, 1]`} /> and
    couple two ingredients. First, an SIR-style contagion equation on
    the <Math tex={String.raw`\beta_i`} /> drawn from emotional-contagion
    models (Fu et al., 2014; Hill et al., 2010) [4, 5]. Second, a linear
    link from stress to desired speed that feeds back into the Social
    Force Model. The coupled system contains two competing effects.
    Higher stress raises desired speed, which in the orderly regime
    shortens evacuation time. Higher stress also raises lateral pressure
    at the bottleneck, which in the panicked regime triggers arch
    formation and lengthens it. The question that follows is the central
    one of this paper: is there an <em>optimal</em> level of collective
    stress, and how does it depend on the size of the crowd?
  </p>

  <p>
    The question admits a partial closed-form answer through a mean-field
    reduction of the contagion ODE, and a quantitative one through
    agent-based simulation. The answer translates into three measurable
    architectural levers: exit width, alarm authority, and visual
    line-of-sight. Each corresponds to one of the three model parameters
    that set the epidemic threshold.
  </p>
</Section>
